== Structured AI Debate ==

Every claim goes through a **adversarial debate**. Different providers argue against each other. An objection only counts as "contested" if it cites specific counter-evidence — unsupported criticism is classified as "doubted" and cannot change a verdict.

{{mermaid}}
flowchart LR
    E[Evidence + Boundaries] --> S1

    subgraph INTERNAL["Internal Debate Pipeline"]
        direction LR
        S1[1. Advocate]
        S4[4. Reconciliation]
        S5[5. Validation]

        subgraph "Parallel Execution"
            S2[2. Self-Consistency x2]
            S3[3. Adversarial Challenge]
        end

        S1 --> S2
        S1 --> S3
        S2 --> S4
        S3 --> S4
    end

    S4 --> S5
    S5 --> O[Final Verdict]

    ANTH["Anthropic API Calls<br/>Advocate, Self-Consistency,<br/>Reconciler, Validator"]
    OPENAI["OpenAI API Call<br/>Challenger (GPT-4.1)"]

    S1 -.-> ANTH
    S2 -.-> ANTH
    S4 -.-> ANTH
    S5 -.-> ANTH
    S3 -.-> OPENAI

    style S1 fill:#e8f5e9,stroke:#2e7d32
    style S2 fill:#e3f2fd,stroke:#1565c0
    style S3 fill:#fff3e0,stroke:#e65100
    style S4 fill:#f3e5f5,stroke:#7b1fa2
    style S5 fill:#fce4ec,stroke:#c2185b
    style INTERNAL fill:#f9fbff,stroke:#90a4ae,color:#000,stroke-width:1.5px
    style ANTH fill:#F3E5F5,stroke:#7B1FA2,color:#4A148C,stroke-width:2px
    style OPENAI fill:#F3E5F5,stroke:#7B1FA2,color:#4A148C,stroke-width:2px
{{/mermaid}}

=== Debate Roles ===

|=Step|=Role|=Function|=Provider
|1|**Advocate**|Build the strongest evidence-backed case for the most supported interpretation|Anthropic (Sonnet)
|2|**Self-Consistency**|Two parallel re-runs at elevated temperature — measures verdict stability|Anthropic (Sonnet)
|3|**Challenger**|Adversarial challenge from a //different provider// for model diversity|OpenAI (GPT-4.1)
|4|**Reconciler**|Final verdict integrating challenge insights and stability data|Anthropic (Sonnet)
|5|**Validator**|Grounding check + direction check (advisory, non-blocking)|Anthropic (Haiku)

(% class="box infomessage" %)
(((
**Cross-provider diversity:** Steps 2 and 3 run in parallel. Using different LLM providers for Advocate vs. Challenger prevents single-model echo-chamber bias — a known weakness in single-provider fact-checking systems.
)))

----

== Verdict Transparency ==

Verdicts are not binary. The system reports a **7-point scale** with confidence levels, so you know whether a claim is overwhelmingly supported, genuinely mixed, or contradicted — and how confident the system is.

{{mermaid}}
flowchart LR
    TRUE["TRUE\n86-100%"]
    MT["MOSTLY\nTRUE\n72-85%"]
    LT["LEANING\nTRUE\n58-71%"]
    MIXED["MIXED /\nUNVERIFIED\n43-57%"]
    LF["LEANING\nFALSE\n29-42%"]
    MF["MOSTLY\nFALSE\n15-28%"]
    FALSE["FALSE\n0-14%"]

    TRUE --- MT --- LT --- MIXED --- LF --- MF --- FALSE

    style TRUE fill:#2e7d32,color:#fff
    style MT fill:#43a047,color:#fff
    style LT fill:#66bb6a,color:#000
    style MIXED fill:#fdd835,color:#000
    style LF fill:#ff9800,color:#000
    style MF fill:#e65100,color:#fff
    style FALSE fill:#b71c1c,color:#fff
{{/mermaid}}

Each verdict includes: truth percentage, confidence tier (High / Medium / Low / Insufficient evidence), supporting and opposing evidence citations, and a full reasoning narrative.

----

== Evidence Quality: Defence in Depth ==

Every piece of evidence passes through **six layers of quality control** before it can influence a verdict. Two phases: pre-verdict evidence quality filtering and post-verdict verdict quality validation.

{{mermaid}}
flowchart LR
    RAW["Raw Evidence\n(LLM extraction)"]:::raw

    subgraph P1["Phase 1: Pre-Verdict Quality"]
        direction LR
        L1["1. Prompt Guidance"]:::phase1
        L2["2. Deterministic Filter\n(length, dedup, category rules)"]:::det
        L3["3. Provenance Validation"]:::det
        L1 --> L2 --> L3
    end

    subgraph P2["Phase 2: Post-Verdict Quality"]
        direction LR
        L4["4. SR Weighting"]:::det
        L5["5. Aggregation Pruning"]:::det
        L6["6. Validator Checks"]:::det
        L4 --> L5 --> L6
    end

    CLEAN["Published Report\n(verdict + warnings)"]:::clean

    RAW --> L1
    L3 --> L4
    L6 --> CLEAN

    classDef raw fill:#f7e8ea,stroke:#cc8f97,color:#5f2a2f,stroke-width:1.5px
    classDef clean fill:#e8f3e8,stroke:#8cb58f,color:#1f4d2a,stroke-width:1.5px
    classDef phase1 fill:#f8fbff,stroke:#8fb2e5,color:#284f8f,stroke-width:1.2px
    classDef det fill:#fdeaea,stroke:#d08b8b,color:#8a2c2c,stroke-width:1.2px
    style P1 fill:#f4f8ff,stroke:#b7cdef,color:#000,stroke-width:1.2px
    style P2 fill:#fffaf2,stroke:#ecd39b,color:#000,stroke-width:1.2px
    linkStyle default stroke:#666,stroke-width:1.6px
{{/mermaid}}

|=Step|=Type|=What happens
|**1. Prompt Guidance**|LLM-guided (quality constraints are expressed in the extraction prompt)|The extraction prompt already pushes the model toward source-grounded, specific, non-hand-wavy evidence instead of vague commentary or unsupported paraphrase.
|**2. Deterministic Filter**|Deterministic|Low-quality evidence is removed with structural pass/fail checks rather than one single score formula: e.g. statementLength < minLength, probativeValue == low, missing URL/excerpt, or statistic without digits. Monitoring formula: falsePositiveRate = highProbativeFiltered / filtered.
|**3. Provenance Validation**|Deterministic|Evidence must remain tied to a real fetched source and valid URL provenance; synthetic or broken provenance paths are rejected before verdicting. There is no single numeric formula here: it is deterministic pass/fail validation of source linkage and provenance integrity.
|**4. SR Weighting**|Hybrid (LLM-generated source scores, deterministic weighting formula)|Each source domain gets a credibility score from the Source Reliability subsystem, then the deterministic weighting step applies formulas such as adjustedTruth = 50 + (originalTruth - 50) * avgWeight and adjustedConfidence = confidence * (0.5 + avgWeight / 2).
|**5. Aggregation Pruning**|Deterministic|Before the final report is produced, tangential or low-value evidence is pruned with threshold logic rather than an LLM judgment: direct claims are always kept, but tangential claims must satisfy evidenceCount >= minEvidence (default 2), and can optionally be required to include at least one medium/high-quality evidence item.
|**6. Validator Checks**|Hybrid (LLM-based validation plus deterministic warning/report logic)|Post-verdict checks look for grounding problems, direction mismatches, and other consistency issues. There is no single universal formula for this row, but deterministic enforcement logic is applied where needed, for example confidence penalties or warning thresholds after the LLM-based validation step.

Source reliability scores are computed per-domain using multi-provider LLM evaluation, with cross-check refinement and persistent caching. A peer-reviewed study carries different weight than a social media post — automatically.

